MOH guideline: Persons who have recovered from COVID-19 and have completed their primary series vaccination do not require an additional booster dose at this point in time (with no expiry date).
If anyone gets covid, MOH should record and issue discharge memo if you still want to implement VDS. Don't over-medicate by asking people who have acquired natural immunity (especially the mild cases) to go for extra/
unnecessary vaccine shots/boosters.

Mucus vs Vaccines

I never really appreciate my mucus before until Covid 19 emerges.

During cold weather especially early morning my body will produce "tonnes" of mucus and fill up my nose to the degree I'm not breathable.

As I grew up, nose congestion has started to minimize but my body was still able to produce excessive mucus when needed.

Mucus plays an important role in keeping us healthy.

Mucus is the interface between us and the outside world.

Mucus lines the moist surfaces of our body like the lungs, sinuses, mouth, stomach, and intestines.

It serves as a line of defense - because anything that you breathe in gets stuck in the mucus.

Bacteria land on the mucus-lined surface of the lungs will get trapped.

In a normal healthy body the little hairs called cilia will push the mucus up and out of the lungs with all the trapped bacteria, viruses, and dust.

Since both our nose & our mouth is the key entry point for Covid 19 virus, peoples with excessive mucus in both the nose and mouth (me) will stop the advancement of the virus through our lungs.

If the majority of the people are not able to produce excessive mucus then MOH may have to create some sort of nasal vaccine because the nasal vaccine is more robust than an injected vaccine.

As the saying goes "Prevention (nasal vaccine) is better than Cure (injected vaccine)".
